    contentEn: [
      "**The £240,000 Bearing That Could Have Cost £800**\n\nA food manufacturing client came to us after a catastrophic gearbox failure: 18-hour production line shutdown, £240,000 in lost output, £45,000 emergency repair. The bearing that caused it had been showing anomalous vibration signatures for 11 days before failure — but no one was watching.\n\nThis is the predictive maintenance problem. The data was there. The failure was preventable. The question is always: how do you turn continuous sensor streams into actionable maintenance schedules?\n\nThe global predictive maintenance market is £18B (2024) growing at 28% CAGR. The ROI case is straightforward: average unplanned downtime costs manufacturers £8,000-£40,000 per hour. A system that prevents 3 failures per year pays for itself in month one.",
      "**Reactive → Preventive → Predictive: The Maintenance Maturity Model**\n\n**Reactive (Break-Fix)**: Replace parts after failure. Low upfront cost, high downtime cost, unpredictable. Suitable only for non-critical, easily replaceable components.\n\n**Preventive (Time-Based)**: Replace parts every N hours regardless of condition. Better than reactive, but 30-50% of parts replaced preventively still have 50-80% of useful life remaining — waste.\n\n**Predictive (Condition-Based)**: Replace parts when sensor data indicates imminent failure. Industry average: 25-30% reduction in maintenance costs, 70-75% reduction in breakdowns, 35-45% reduction in downtime.\n\n**Prescriptive (AI-Optimised)**: ML not only predicts failure but recommends optimal maintenance window based on production schedule, parts availability, and technician capacity. This is where MachineGuard operates.",
      "**Data Pipeline: From Sensor to Prediction**\n\nA production predictive maintenance system requires:\n\n**Sensors**: Vibration (accelerometers at 25.6 kHz sampling), temperature (PT100 RTD sensors), current (Hall effect, non-invasive), oil particle count (optional, for gearboxes). Critical: sample at appropriate frequency — 25.6 kHz captures bearing defect frequencies (BPFO, BPFI, BSF) that 100Hz sensors miss entirely.\n\n**Edge Processing**: Raw sensor data volume is enormous — 25.6 kHz × 3 axes × 50 machines = 3.84 million samples/second. Edge devices (Raspberry Pi 4 or NVIDIA Jetson) run FFT and feature extraction locally: RMS, kurtosis, crest factor, frequency band energy. This reduces bandwidth to 1,200 features/minute per machine.\n\n**Time-Series Database**: InfluxDB or TimescaleDB. Do not use a relational database for sensor data — query performance degrades catastrophically beyond 100M rows without time-series optimisation.\n\n**Feature Engineering**: Rolling statistics (mean, std, skewness over 1min/1h/24h windows), rate of change, cross-sensor correlations (vibration × temperature). This is where domain expertise matters — a mechanical engineer knows that kurtosis > 4.0 on the bearing frequency is significant.",
      "**ML Models for Failure Prediction**\n\nThree model types serve different prediction horizons:\n\n**Anomaly Detection (Unsupervised, 0-24h horizon)**: Isolation Forest or LSTM Autoencoder trained on normal operation. When reconstruction error exceeds threshold, trigger alert. No labelled failure data required — ideal for new equipment.\n\n**Remaining Useful Life (RUL) Regression (1-30 day horizon)**: LSTM or Temporal Fusion Transformer predicts days until failure. Requires historical run-to-failure data (expensive to collect — consider NASA CMAPSS dataset for initial validation).\n\n**Binary Classification (Week-ahead, 7-14 day horizon)**: XGBoost trained on features extracted 7 days before known failures. Simpler than RUL, more actionable — maintenance schedulers want 'will it fail this week?' not 'exactly 9.3 days remaining'.\n\nMachineGuard uses all three in an ensemble: anomaly detection for immediate alerts, RUL for maintenance planning, binary classification for weekly work order generation.",
      "**Results and Implementation Timeline**\n\nMachineGuard deployment at a UK food manufacturer (14 CNC machines, 8 conveyor motors, 6 compressors):\n\n- Unplanned downtime: −73% (from 340h/year to 92h/year)\n- Maintenance cost: −31% (optimised parts ordering, reduced overtime)\n- False alarm rate: 4.2% (industry benchmark: 8-12%)\n- Time to first value: 6 weeks (data collection: 2 weeks, model training: 2 weeks, integration: 2 weeks)\n\n**Implementation roadmap:**\n1. Sensor audit and installation (2-3 weeks)\n2. Data collection — minimum 8 weeks of normal operation before training\n3. Baseline model training and threshold calibration (2 weeks)\n4. Integration with CMMS (computerised maintenance management system) — work order auto-generation\n5. Operator training and dashboard rollout (1 week)\n6. Continuous improvement cycle — monthly model retraining with new failure events\n\nThe key lesson: start with your most critical, failure-prone equipment. A Pareto analysis typically shows that 20% of machines cause 80% of unplanned downtime — focus there first and demonstrate ROI before scaling.",
    ],
