      "## The verdict upfront: Python for production ML, R for statistical research\n\nIf you're building ML models that will run in production — a microservice, an API endpoint, a scheduled pipeline — choose Python. If you're doing statistical modelling, clinical trial analysis, econometrics, or academic research where the output is a paper or report, R may still be the better fit. For most UK business ML projects, Python wins by a substantial margin.",
      "## Python's ecosystem advantages\n\nThe Python ML stack is unmatched in breadth and production-readiness: scikit-learn for classical ML, PyTorch and TensorFlow for deep learning, Hugging Face Transformers for NLP, LangChain/LlamaIndex for LLM applications, MLflow and Weights & Biases for experiment tracking, FastAPI for serving models, and Airflow/Prefect for orchestration. Every major cloud provider's ML platform (Azure ML, SageMaker, Vertex AI) has first-class Python support.",
      "## Where R still wins\n\nR's statistical packages remain best-in-class for specific domains: survival analysis (survival package), mixed-effects models (lme4), Bayesian modelling (Stan via RStan, brms), time series econometrics (forecast, tseries), and clinical trial analysis (where R is the FDA-preferred language for statistical submissions). R's ggplot2 produces publication-quality visualisations that Python's matplotlib/seaborn still don't match aesthetically.",
      "## UK job market comparison\n\nSearching UK ML/data science job postings: Python is required in 87% of ML engineer roles, 79% of data scientist roles, and 95% of MLOps roles. R appears in 23% of data scientist roles (mostly pharma, finance, academic) and under 5% of ML engineer roles. Salary data: Python ML engineers average £72,000 versus R data scientists at £58,000, largely reflecting the production vs research split.",
      "## The practical answer for most UK businesses\n\nFor a UK business commissioning an ML project: specify Python unless you have an existing R codebase or your use case is explicitly statistical/actuarial/clinical. Python's production deployment story (Docker → FastAPI → cloud ML platform) is far more mature. If your data science team works in R and needs to productionise models, consider MLflow for model packaging (language-agnostic) or rewriting the inference code in Python while keeping R for research.",
