    wordCount: 2000,
    contentEn: [
      "## Why time series forecasting matters for UK businesses\n\nEvery UK business with repeating cycles — weekly retail sales, monthly energy consumption, quarterly demand, daily website traffic — can benefit from better forecasting. Typical business impact: a retailer reducing inventory by 10% while maintaining service levels, an energy company better balancing supply contracts, a SaaS company predicting monthly churn before it happens. The question is not whether to forecast, but which method to use.",
      "## ARIMA/SARIMA: the statistical baseline\n\nARIMA (AutoRegressive Integrated Moving Average) remains the right starting point for datasets with fewer than 1,000 observations, where interpretability is critical, or where the business has existing ARIMA models to benchmark against. Python's statsmodels implements ARIMA; pmdarima's auto_arima automates order selection. SARIMA adds seasonal components — essential for monthly/quarterly data with yearly cycles (e.g., UK retail Christmas spike, heating demand). Limitation: ARIMA assumes linear relationships and struggles with complex multi-seasonal patterns.",
      "## Prophet: production-ready forecasting with business calendars\n\nFacebook Prophet (now maintained by the open-source community) is ideal for UK business forecasting because it natively handles: UK public holidays (England, Scotland, Wales, NI), multiple seasonalities (daily, weekly, yearly), changepoints (product launches, price changes), and is robust to missing data. Prophet is not the most accurate method, but it is highly interpretable, easy to tune without deep time series expertise, and reliably deployable in production. Best for: retail sales, website traffic, energy consumption, HR headcount planning.",
      "## LSTM and Transformer models: when deep learning is justified\n\nLSTM (Long Short-Term Memory) networks and Temporal Fusion Transformers (TFT) outperform classical methods when: the dataset has 10,000+ observations, multiple related time series (e.g., all SKUs in a category), or complex non-linear patterns. N-BEATS and N-HiTS (from the Nixtla library) are newer deep learning architectures that consistently win forecasting competitions. Critical warning: deep learning forecasting models require careful validation — they can overfit aggressively and produce confident-looking but wildly wrong predictions outside their training distribution.",
      "## NeuralProphet: the bridge between Prophet and LSTM\n\nNeuralProphet (PyTorch-based Prophet replacement) combines Prophet's interpretability and business calendar features with neural network components that capture non-linear patterns. It trains faster than pure LSTM approaches and provides component-wise decomposition (trend, seasonality, autoregression) that business stakeholders can understand. Recommended as the default starting point for UK retail and operations forecasting when Prophet accuracy is insufficient.",
      "## Evaluation: MAPE is not enough\n\nMean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE) is the most commonly reported metric but is problematic for intermittent demand (division by zero when actuals are near zero) and asymmetric costs. For UK retail: use WMAPE (Weighted MAPE, inventory-value-weighted) and Bias (systematic over/under-forecasting). For energy: use MAE in MWh with a cost-of-imbalance weighting. Always evaluate across multiple test periods including seasonal peaks.",
    ],
