    wordCount: 1900,
    contentEn: [
      "## The three-phase cost structure of UK ML projects\n\nMost UK ML engagements follow a three-phase commercial structure: Discovery/Data Audit (weeks 1-3, fixed price), Proof of Concept (weeks 4-10, fixed price or T&M), and Production Deployment + MLOps (months 3-12, typically milestone-based or monthly retainer). Each phase has a distinct risk profile — the Discovery phase is low risk and low cost; skipping it is the most common cause of expensive project failures.",
      "## Phase 1: Discovery and Data Audit (£3,000 – £12,000)\n\nTypically 2-3 weeks. Deliverables: data quality assessment across all candidate datasets, ML feasibility assessment (can the problem be solved with available data?), ROI modelling (what is the expected business impact?), technical architecture recommendation, and a PoC scope document. Red flag: any agency quoting a full project without a paid discovery phase is guessing at your data quality — this always ends badly.",
      "## Phase 2: Proof of Concept (£15,000 – £60,000)\n\nTypically 4-8 weeks. A PoC demonstrates the ML approach works on your data with a representative sample — it is NOT production-ready. Deliverables: trained baseline model, evaluation metrics on hold-out test data, explainability analysis (SHAP), data pipeline prototype, and a go/no-go recommendation for production. PoC pricing varies significantly by complexity: a churn model on clean CRM data is £15,000–£25,000; a computer vision defect detection system is £35,000–£60,000.",
      "## Phase 3: Production Deployment (£30,000 – £150,000+)\n\nTypically 8-20 weeks. This converts the PoC into a production system with: REST API or batch inference pipeline, integration with your existing systems (CRM, ERP, data warehouse), CI/CD for model updates, monitoring dashboard (data drift, model performance metrics), documentation, and handover training. Add 30-50% to Phase 3 estimates if you have legacy systems that require significant integration work.",
      "## MLOps retainer (£3,000 – £15,000/month)\n\nModels degrade as real-world data distributions shift — this is not a bug, it is the nature of ML. A monthly MLOps retainer covers: performance monitoring, retraining triggers and execution, A/B testing of model updates, infrastructure maintenance, and incident response. For models driving significant business decisions (credit, fraud, pricing), skipping this phase is false economy.",
      "## Where to save money on UK ML projects\n\nUse open-source models and frameworks (scikit-learn, PyTorch) rather than AutoML platforms (which charge £20,000+/year for what a competent data scientist can do in Python for free). Phase the engagement — commit to Discovery + PoC only, then evaluate before committing to Phase 3. Choose a regional agency over a London Big 4 for equivalent technical work (30-40% cost reduction). Cloud credits: AWS, Azure, and GCP all offer startup/SME credit programmes worth £10,000–£50,000 that can offset infrastructure costs.",
    ],
