      "## The Cambridge ML market: what makes it different\n\nCambridge's 'Silicon Fen' AI ecosystem is unlike any other UK cluster. With 600+ AI startups, 800+ ML researchers at the University of Cambridge, and anchor companies like ARM, AstraZeneca, and Wayve, Cambridge has the UK's highest per-capita concentration of ML expertise. This creates a uniquely demanding client base: Cambridge deep tech founders expect research-grade rigour, not 'we built a logistic regression model' deliverables.\n\nFor an ML consultant engaging Cambridge clients, the baseline expectation is: rigorous cross-validation (proper train/val/test splits, no data leakage), ablation studies to justify architectural decisions, reproducibility documentation, and investor-grade evaluation frameworks. Cambridge VC firms like Cambridge Innovation Capital and Parkwalk Advisors expect to see model validation reports as part of Series A due diligence.",
      "## What Cambridge deep tech startups need from an ML consultant\n\nBased on Cambridge ecosystem patterns, four common engagement types: 1) **PoC to Series A validation** — academic spinout needs commercial-grade ML prototype for investor presentation. Requires: clean data pipeline, reproducible training code, documented benchmarks against SOTA baselines. 2) **Production engineering for research models** — excellent research model needs production wrapper: FastAPI serving, monitoring, CI/CD for model updates. 3) **Independent validation** — second opinion on in-house ML team's model claims before investor or regulatory submission. 4) **UKRI/Innovate UK technical writing** — ML methodology sections for grant applications require specific rigour framing.",
      "## Innovate UK grants: what ML consultants need to know\n\nCambridge startups disproportionately use Innovate UK funding. For ML projects, the key funding streams are: Innovate UK SMART (up to £500,000 for R&D projects), UKRI Future Leaders Fellowships (for academic spinouts), and Innovate UK Advanced Manufacturing (for applied ML in manufacturing). A qualifying ML consultant should be able to: frame the ML project as genuine R&D (not mere application of existing methods), write TRL (Technology Readiness Level) assessments, articulate the technical uncertainty that makes the work eligible for R&D tax credits, and structure work packages to match Innovate UK milestones.",
